@node "Document_0" "What is Startup-Optimizer?"
Startup-Optimizer is a CLI-based tool for optimizing the startup-speed of
your system.
The basic idea of this program differs a little from most of the other
disk-optimizers and it is quite simple: Loading one big file is
faster than loading many small ones. And that's how it works.
Startup-Optimizer examines your startup-sequence and sorts out all
filenames of commands or tools that could be found on your disk or HD,
loads them, puts them into one archive-file and modifies the
startup-sequence, so that during startup the archive-file will be loaded
first and all files in it are copied to the ram-disk and are started from
there. At the end of it all those files can of course be deleted from RAM:
again.
This is rather useful for users without HD, because the efficiency on
floppy-disks is bigger than on HDs and besides all important commands can
be left in RAM:.
@endnode

@node "Document_1" "System Requirements      "
Startup-Optimizer should run on all Amigas with all Kickstart versions.
No external Libs needed.
@endnode

@node "Document_2" "Installation             "
The installation is very easy.

Just copy @{fg highlight}SUO@{fg text}                   to @{fg shine}C:@{fg text}
      and @{fg highlight}SUO-REMOVE@{fg text}            to @{fg shine}C:@{fg text}

Don't rename the file SUO !
@endnode

@node "Document_3" "Usage                    "
The general usage is:

@{fg fill}SUO [-<options>] <command> [<batchfile>] [<additional filelist>]@{fg text}

Where <command> is one of:   r   Read
                             w   Write

And   <options> are:         a   Add and specify filelist
                             b   Specify batch-file
                             i   Print info while writing

With the command WRITE you can create an archive-file. Startup-Optimizer
then works as described in 'What is StartUpOptimizer?'.

SUO w                     is standard
SUO -b w abc              Startup-Optimizer doesn't examine
                          'S:startup-sequence', but that batch-file you
                          specified here: 'abc'
SUO -a w def              examines 'S:startup-sequence' (standard) and
                          adds some files to the archive that you listed up
                          in a file named 'def'
SUO -abi w abc def        examines the batchfile 'abc',
                          adds the files to the archive listed up in 'def',
                          prints out which files are found and added to the
                          archive (incl. length)
SUO r                     reads the archive and puts all files to RAM:
                          (usually only used by the modified
                           startup-sequence)

After the use of the WRITE command a modified Startup-Sequence/Batch-File
can be found in your S:-drawer called 'Startup-Sequence.SUO'.
Also you can find a new file named 'Startup-Files.SUO' in yor S: drawer
(the archive-file).
To delete the files from RAM: again that were used by Startup-Optimizer
just add the command
SUO-REMOVE
somewhere at the end of your Startup-Sequence/Batch-File.

You want to see some > @{"Examples" link "Examples" 0} < ?
@endnode

@node "Examples" "Examples"
In the following examples a > at the beginning of a line means that this
is your input and { ... } means that this is an output on the screen.

@{"Example1" link "Examples1" 0}        Standard usage
@{"Example2" link "Examples2" 0}        Usage with another batch-file
@{"Example3" link "Examples4" 0}        Usage with additional file-list
@{"Example4" link "Examples3" 0}        Usage with another batch-file and an additional file-list
