@node "Examples1" "Example1"
Your Startup-Sequence:
_____________________________________________________________________
.
.
.
assign  >NIL: T: RAM:T
mount   >NIL: DEVS:DosDrivers/~(#?.info)
iprefs
endcli
_____________________________________________________________________

>SUO -i w

{
StartUp-Optimizer V1.0 by Martin Kaiser

------------------------- File-List -------------------------
ASSIGN                                                   3220
MOUNT                                                    6588
IPREFS                                                  13164
}

Your new 'Startup-Sequence.SUO':
_____________________________________________________________________
C:SUO r
.
.
.
RAM:assign  >NIL: T: RAM:T
RAM:mount   >NIL: DEVS:DosDrivers/~(#?.info)
RAM:iprefs
endcli
_____________________________________________________________________

@endnode

@node "Examples2" "Example2"
Your batch-file named 'batch.bat':
_____________________________________________________________________
assign  >NIL: T: RAM:T
mount   >NIL: DEVS:DosDrivers/~(#?.info)
_____________________________________________________________________

>SUO -ib w batch.bat

{
StartUp-Optimizer V1.0 by Martin Kaiser

------------------------- File-List -------------------------
ASSIGN                                                   3220
MOUNT                                                    6588
}

Your new 'Startup-Sequence.SUO':
_____________________________________________________________________
C:SUO r
RAM:assign  >NIL: T: RAM:T
RAM:mount   >NIL: DEVS:DosDrivers/~(#?.info)
_____________________________________________________________________

If you don't want the files ASSIGN and MOUNT in RAM: after execution
of your batch-file then you have to add 'SUO-REMOVE' (with a text-ed.
like e.g. CED) at the end of the batch:
_____________________________________________________________________
C:SUO r
RAM:assign  >NIL: T: RAM:T
RAM:mount   >NIL: DEVS:DosDrivers/~(#?.info)
SUO-REMOVE
_____________________________________________________________________

It would be even better to first add SUO-REMOVE to your original
batch-file and then run Startup-Optimizer. The command 'SUO-REMOVE'
will then be included in the archive-file. The advantage would be the
higher speed in executing the batch. The result would then look like this:
_____________________________________________________________________
C:SUO r
RAM:assign  >NIL: T: RAM:T
RAM:mount   >NIL: DEVS:DosDrivers/~(#?.info)
RAM:SUO-REMOVE
_____________________________________________________________________

Of course you only get good results in speed if your batch-files are
bigger than that one shown here.

@endnode

@node "Examples3" "Example4"
If you want to use Startup-Optimizer not with the Startup-Sequence, but
with another batch-file AND use an additional file-list,too then you have
first to specify the batch-file and then the additional file-list
(see general usage):

>SUO -abi w yourbatchfile.bat youradditionalfilelist.txt

@endnode


@node "Examples4" "Example3"
Your Startup-Sequence:
_____________________________________________________________________
.
.
.
assign  >NIL: T: RAM:T
mount   >NIL: DEVS:DosDrivers/~(#?.info)
iprefs
run     myprogram
endcli
_____________________________________________________________________

Your additional-list named 'addlist.txt':
_____________________________________________________________________
dh1:myprogram
c:dir
c:more
_____________________________________________________________________


>SUO -ia w addlist.txt

{
StartUp-Optimizer V1.0 by Martin Kaiser

------------------------- File-List -------------------------
ASSIGN                                                   3220
MOUNT                                                    6588
IPREFS                                                  13164
MYPROGRAM                                               33333
DIR                                                      3440
MORE                                                    11032
}

Your new 'Startup-Sequence.SUO':
_____________________________________________________________________
C:SUO r
.
.
.
RAM:assign  >NIL: T: RAM:T
RAM:mount   >NIL: DEVS:DosDrivers/~(#?.info)
RAM:iprefs
run         RAM:myprogram
endcli
_____________________________________________________________________

The command 'run' could neither be found in the current directory
nor in the C:-directory, so it is not included in the archive-file.
In 'addlist.txt' are 3 files listed that you also want to include in
the archive-file. The entry 'dh1:myprogram' could be found and is
included.
Also the line 'run myprogram' will be changed into 'run RAM:myprogram',
because this file will be in RAM: at that time, too.
If you want 'myprogram' to be put into the archive-file then
you MUST specify it in an additional file as shown above, otherwise
Startup-Optimizer only recognizes 'myprogram' as an argument of 'run'
and ignores it.

@endnode

@node "Examples5" "Example5"
If you don't have a HD and need most of the CLI-commands very often then
do this (however your Startup-Sequence looks like):

>LIST C: >RAM:batch.txt
>SUO -a w RAM:batch.txt

- Your Startup-Sequence will be modified and saved in the file
  'Startup-Files.SUO' (see examples above)
- and all commands in your C: directory will be put into the archive, too

After booting your disk all C:-commands are in RAM:. This method should be
much faster than copying one file after the other to RAM: in your
Startup-Sequence.
@endnode

@node "Document_5" "Speed"
You have to find out to handle Startup-Optimizer so that the
efficiency is best on your system.
You should only use it for bigger batch-files (not for threeliners).
If you use it for small batch-files the speed could then even be lower
than before!
I tried it out on an A500 with booting from a Startup-Sequence on disk
and got a speed that was approximately 40% better than before.
@endnode

